"{\n  \"text\": \"Your gut microbiome is responsible for a lot more than just digesting your foods. What they're showing now in a lot of recent research is that it controls brain function, it controls organ function, that the lot of the body's processes, including the immune system, the processing of nutrients and vitamins and all these other things are actually done by the gut microbes and then distributed out to the body. In a weird way, your gut microbiome is a hive mind that maintains your body. So as opposed to thinking yourself as, and this is the thought experiment, as a brain supported by a body. What if you are a group of anaerobic bacteria acting like a hive mind? And by anaerobic I mean thrives without oxygen, that are trying to live in an environment full of oxygen. And what if they've woven a membrane to protect themselves and to function in this world? And what if you are that membrane? What if this brain that we consider ourselves to be us is actually just uh the division in turn in charge of external processing? Anyway, just a thought experiment. See y'all. Thanks. And I've got to pay the bills. Eat my sauerkraut. Fermented foods are good for you. Thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Your gut microbiome is responsible for a lot more than just digesting your foods.\",\n      \"start\": 0.08,\n      \"end\": 3.6,\n      \"duration\": 3.52,\n      \"confidence\": 0.998,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Y\",\n          \"start\": 0.08,\n          \"end\": 0.16,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.994\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"our\",\n          \"start\": 0.16,\n          \"end\": 0.24,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" gut\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" m